x4freetext: The differential gamma production cross-sections at
110 and respectively 150 degrees were derived
normalising point by point the HPGe yield to the 235U
fission chamber yield and to the 235U(n,f) cross
section.
The following corrections were done:
- Multiplication of original data (BgNS Transactions
Rev.C91(2015)064618) to correct for fission chamber
efficiency redetermination.
- for the distance between positions of the Cr2O3
sample and the position of the fission chamber;
- for gamma-ray detection efficiency;
- for extended volume of source and self-attenuation
of the gamma rays in the Cr2O3 sample;
- for angular distribution;
- for Gauss quadrature;
- for multiple scattering and attenuation of the
neutron beam in the Cr2O3 sample and its thin Al
can.
Total errors for the cross sections were
deduced by combining partial errors from various
sources in quadrature. Error sources considered were:
- 235U(n,f) cross section uncertainties were point
dependent and are given above together the 235U(n,f)
cross-sections values;
HPGe efficiencies errors for the
two detectors, ranging from 1.32% at 0.64 MeV up to
1.94% at 2.33 MeV gamma ray energy. This errors
includes the statistical counting errors, calibration
source activity error and MCNP simulations error;
Fission chamber efficiency uncertainty was
Statistical counting errors for HPGe
detectors and fission chamber, ranging from 1.4% at
2 MeV to 3% at at 18 MeV
The analytical expressions employed are detailed in
the above mentioned NIM paper. Together with the list
of errors on the quantities in these expressions
listed above this will allow the evaluator to
construct the covariance matrix. In this we comply
with the method recommended by F.Froehner JEFF report
18, OECD-NEA Paris (2000) and D.L.Smith, Neutron
Physics and Nuclear Data in Science and Technology,
Vol.4, OECD-NEA, Paris ISBN 0-89448-036-7 (1991)
By Arjan Plompen (2015-11-24):
We used a value of 0.984(16) as the fission chamber
efficiency, which should have been 0.861(10). The
correction factor to apply to the data is therefore
0.875(10). See p55 of EUR 25208 EN for these values.
